## 9. Accuracy & Error Sources

### Sync Marker

| Error Source               | Magnitude | Notes                                                                                  |
| -------------------------- | --------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| rAF jitter                 | ±0.5–2ms  | Not a timing input; used only as a diagnostics signal (the sync decode is post-hoc) |
| Tab throttling / sleep     | catastrophic | Marker timeline breaks; UI must force a re-record                                   |
| Codec macroblocks          | depends on ROI size | Too-small marker can corrupt Gray bits / phase; enforce minimum visible ROI        |

**Frontend's responsibility:** keep the Sync Marker visible and continuous during recording, and provide the marker specification (bit count, cycle count, ROI dimensions) to Python so it can decode Gray code + grating phase deterministically.

### Frame Scrubber

The scrubber has no accuracy implications — it is a display tool. PNG decode fidelity is lossless by definition.

### Canvas Overlay

- Trajectory rendering uses float64 positions. The `toCanvas()` transform is linear with no rounding until the final `lineTo()` call. Sub-pixel positions are preserved in the store even if rendered at integer canvas pixels.
- Hit testing uses frame-coordinate distances, not canvas-coordinate distances. This is correct regardless of zoom level.

### Export

- CSV values are formatted to 4 decimal places (values are typically O(1) m/s). Underlying `float64` precision is preserved in JSON export.
- PDF export uses `html2canvas` rasterisation at 2× device pixel ratio. This is for visual output only; scientists should use CSV/JSON for computation.

