## 12. Performance Considerations

### Time Complexity

| Operation            | Complexity                     | Notes                                          |
| -------------------- | ------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------- |
| Trajectory rendering | O(N_balls × N_frames) per draw | 3 × 900 = 2700 ops; < 2ms                      |
| Hit testing          | O(N_balls × 5)                 | Only ±2 frames searched                        |
| CSV export           | O(N_balls × N_frames)          | String formatting; < 10ms                      |
| PDF export           | O(DOM area)                    | html2canvas ~500ms; acceptable (not real-time) |

### Memory Usage

| Buffer                   | Size                            |
| ------------------------ | ------------------------------- |
| FrameScrubber cache      | 50 × ~500KB = 25 MB             |
| `chunks: Blob[]` (phone) | Up to ~750 MB for 60s @ 100Mbps |
| `BallTrack[]` in store   | 3 × 900 × ~100 bytes = ~270 KB  |
| `PhysicsResult`          | < 100 KB                        |

### Bandwidth

- WebRTC preview stream: ~1–5 Mbps per camera (H.264 at browser-negotiated bitrate). LAN handles this trivially.
- PNG frame transfer (scrubber): ~500 KB/request. Pre-loaded in window of 20 → ~10 MB burst. LAN handles this trivially.
- Video upload: 100 Mbps × 60s = ~750 MB per phone. LAN (802.11ac): ~500 Mbps theoretical; expect ~50–100s transfer time. Acceptable.

### Bottlenecks

- **Phone upload time**: The primary user-perceived bottleneck. Nothing can be done; it is inherent to the 100 Mbps recording strategy. Progress bar makes it acceptable.
- **PDF export**: html2canvas is slow for large DOM trees. Mitigation: use a dedicated, simplified DOM subtree for PDF capture (not the full page).
- **TrajectoryCanvas on low-end PCs**: If N_frames > 3000 (5min @ 10fps), batch drawing into path segments, skip rendering frames > 100 away from currentFrame.

